<tableCitation box="[435,516,616,640]" captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="5.[168,220,417,437]" captionText="Table 2. Species list of medium-sized and large land mammals detected with camera traps in eight sites along the Terminos-Centla wetlands. Conservation status according to the IUCN Red List (2014) and Mexican legislation (SEMARNAT 2010). IUCN categories: (LC) Least Concern, (DD) Data Deficient, (NT) NearThreatened,and (V) Vulnerable.NOM- 059: (Th) Threatened, (En) Endangered,and (SP) Special protection.The method by which the species registration was obtained in the study sites is indicated by a P when it was obtained through camera traps, L when it was obtained through literature, and O when it was obtained by direct observation (of living animals or organic remains from traffic accidents or found in the field).In the cases where literature was the information source,the superscript indicates the specific citation." pageId="7" pageNumber="718">Table 2</tableCitation>
; 
<figureCitation box="[528,632,616,640]" captionStart="Figures 2–15" captionStartId="6.[168,239,1804,1824]" captionTargetBox="[168,1419,160,1780]" captionTargetId="figure-14@6.[168,1419,160,1780]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figures 2–15. Photographs of the medium and large–sized mammal species recorded in the Terminos- Centla wetlands, in southeastern Mexico.2. Philander opossum. 3. Didelphis sp. 4. Dasypus novemcinctus. 5. Tamandua mexicana. 6. Cyclopes didactylus. 7. Ateles geoffroyi. 8. Alouatta villosa. 9. Sylvilagus floridanus. 10. Sciurus sp. 11. Coendou mexicanus. 12. Dasyprocta punctata. 13. Cuniculus paca. 14. Herpailurus yagouaroundi; 15. Leopardus pardalis. 16. Leopardus wiedii." pageId="7" pageNumber="718">Figure 11</figureCitation>
.
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[168,775,616,843]" pageId="7" pageNumber="718">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kerr" baseAuthorityYear="1792" box="[206,422,650,674]" class="Mammalia" family="Erethizontidae" genus="Coendou" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="7" pageNumber="718" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mexicanus">
<emphasis box="[206,422,650,674]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="718">Coendou mexicanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only erethizontid in southern 
<collectingCountry box="[209,290,684,708]" name="Mexico" pageId="7" pageNumber="718">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(Hall 1981). The presence of spines on most of the body make this species unique in the region (
<bibRefCitation author="Reid F" pageId="7" pageNumber="718" refId="ref12602" refString="Reid F (2009) A field guide to the mammals of Central America and Southeast Mexico. 2 nd ed. Oxford University Press, New York, 384 pp." type="book" year="2009">Reid 2009</bibRefCitation>
). We classify this species as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kerr" baseAuthorityYear="1792" box="[555,775,751,775]" class="Mammalia" family="Erethizontidae" genus="Coendou" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="7" pageNumber="718" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mexicanus">
<emphasis box="[555,775,751,775]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="718">Coendou mexicanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and not 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kerr" baseAuthorityYear="1792" box="[270,519,785,809]" class="Mammalia" family="Erethizontidae" genus="Sphiggurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="7" pageNumber="718" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mexicanus">
<emphasis box="[270,519,785,809]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="718">Sphiggurus mexicanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
following 
<bibRefCitation author="Voss RS &amp; Hubbard C &amp; Jansa SA" pageId="7" pageNumber="718" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref13289" refString="Voss RS, Hubbard C, Jansa SA (2013) Phylogenetic relationships of New World porcupines (Rodentia, Erethizontidae): implications for taxonomy, morphological evolution, and biogeography. American Museum Novitates 3769: 1 - 36. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 3769.2" type="journal article" year="2013">Voss et al. (2013)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Ramirez-Pulido J &amp; Gonzalez-Ruiz N &amp; Gardner AL &amp; Arroyo-Cabrales J" box="[291,600,819,843]" pageId="7" pageNumber="718" pagination="1 - 69" refId="ref12511" refString="Ramirez-Pulido J, Gonzalez-Ruiz N, Gardner AL, Arroyo-Cabrales J (2014) List of Recent land mammals of Mexico. Special Publications of the Museum of Texas Tech University 63: 1 - 69." type="journal article" year="2014">Ramirez-Pulido et al. (2014)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
